---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const figBase = '/learning/notebooklm';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="NotebookLM — Getting Started"
  description="From creating a notebook, organizing sources, and asking questions, to saving notes — a walkthrough for first-time NotebookLM users."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container nb-basics">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Getting Started: From creating a notebook to organizing key points</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          NotebookLM turns the materials you already have into a conversational knowledge space.
          Drop in PDFs, webpages, YouTube transcripts, Google Docs, or audio files, and then use
          chat to ask for the main points, compare sources, or produce summaries — with inline
          citations so you can trace answers back to the original text.
        </p>
        <p class="platform-note">
          <span class="platform-note__label">Platform note</span>
          The walkthrough below is based on the <strong>desktop interface</strong>,
          as the mobile app still has some limitations around source import and notes.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Section 1: Pricing -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Pricing tiers</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        NotebookLM comes in four tiers: <strong>Standard, Plus, Pro, and Ultra</strong>.
        Standard is the free tier that any personal Google account can use directly.
        If you have Google AI Plus, Google AI Pro, Google AI Ultra, or a qualifying
        Workspace / Workspace for Education license, you may receive higher usage limits.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        For first-time users, Standard is enough to start with. It is usually only once you
        begin working on a sizable project, a research case, or team collaboration that an
        upgrade starts to make a clear difference.
      </p>

      <div class="plan-table-wrapper">
        <table class="plan-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Item</th>
              <th scope="col">Standard<span class="plan-table__sub">Free</span></th>
              <th scope="col">Plus</th>
              <th scope="col">Pro</th>
              <th scope="col">Ultra</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Notebooks</th>
              <td>100</td>
              <td>200</td>
              <td>500</td>
              <td>500</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Sources per notebook</th>
              <td>50</td>
              <td>100</td>
              <td>300</td>
              <td>600</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Chat queries / day</th>
              <td>50</td>
              <td>200</td>
              <td>500</td>
              <td>5,000</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th scope="row">Audio Overviews</th>
              <td>3</td>
              <td>6</td>
              <td>20</td>
              <td>200</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph plan-note">
        Standard also includes 3 Video Overviews per day, plus 10 per day each for Reports,
        Flashcards, and Quizzes. Daily limits reset every 24 hours and monthly limits every
        30 days. <strong>Custom chat and analytics</strong> are available to everyone, but
        <strong>advanced sharing</strong> is a paid feature.
      </p>

      <section class="concept-card">
        <p class="concept-card__label">Which plan should you look at?</p>
        <p class="concept-card__body">
          For personal use, check the <strong>Google AI plans</strong>. For an organization
          account, see whether your school or company <strong>already has a license</strong>.
          If it is a managed account, an administrator will also need to enable NotebookLM
          access before you can use it.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: Create a notebook -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Creating a notebook</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Using NotebookLM is a bit like opening a separate folder for each topic.
        Open NotebookLM, click <strong>"Create new notebook"</strong> (Figure 1),
        and then add sources directly in the dialog that appears (center of Figure 2).
        This step matters, because NotebookLM is not designed for you to dump everything into
        one big pool. The idea is to
        <strong>split different topics into different notebooks</strong>, so that later questions
        and organization don't interfere with each other.
      </p>

      <figure class="figure">
        <img src={`${figBase}/建立新的筆記本.png`} alt="NotebookLM home page, showing the 'Create new notebook' button" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>Figure 1. Creating a new notebook</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <figure class="figure">
        <img src={`${figBase}/新增來源.png`} alt="Add-source dialog, with the notebook name field highlighted in the top-left" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>Figure 2. Adding sources (the notebook-name field is in the top-left)</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        In practice, it helps to name the notebook by <strong>topic</strong> from the start,
        rather than using something generic. Instead of just "Midterm," try
        "Marketing Management midterm — key points," "Thesis interview transcripts," or
        "Career talk notes" — names that make the purpose obvious at a glance.
        As your notebooks grow in number, this tends to save a lot of searching and keeps
        unrelated material from getting mixed up. The rename field sits in the top-left
        of Figure 2.
      </p>

      <!-- Section 3: Add and organize sources -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Adding and organizing sources</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The core idea in NotebookLM is simple: <strong>good sources come before good answers</strong>.
        Officially, a "source" is defined as a static copy imported into the app, which
        NotebookLM then uses as the basis for answering questions and organizing material.
        In other words, the better the quality of what you put in, the steadier its output
        tends to be.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">The supported source types are fairly broad:</p>
      <div class="source-grid">
        <span class="source-chip">PDF</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Google Docs</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Google Slides</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Google Sheets</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Web URL</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Public YouTube videos</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Audio files</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Pasted text</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Images</span>
        <span class="source-chip">docx / txt / md / csv / pptx / ePub</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Selected Gemini Chats</span>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Each source can hold up to <strong>500,000 words</strong>; for local uploads, the file
        size limit is <strong>200 MB</strong>. Standard allows up to 50 sources per notebook,
        with higher limits at paid tiers.
      </p>

      <section class="caution-card">
        <p class="caution-card__label">Three common misconceptions about source import</p>
        <ul class="caution-card__numbered">
          <li>
            <strong>Web import only captures text</strong> — it does not pull in images,
            embedded videos, or sub-pages, and paywalled content is not supported.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>YouTube import brings in the caption transcript, not the video itself</strong>
            — so the video must be public and have captions; videos with no spoken content won't work.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Most sources are static copies</strong> — Google Docs can be manually re-synced
            in NotebookLM after the original updates, but for many other source types, editing
            the original does not flow back automatically.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        When organizing sources, it helps <strong>not to pour everything in at once</strong>.
        A better habit is to keep only the materials that are genuinely relevant to the topic
        and reasonably trustworthy, and then rename each source clearly — for example,
        "Lecture handout, Ch. 3," "Interview transcript A," or "Official product page."
        This way, when you ask questions later, it's easier to pinpoint which source an
        answer is drawing from.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        One small technique worth knowing: once a notebook contains a lot of material,
        you can <strong>check only a few sources</strong> in the source panel on the left
        (see the arrow in Figure 3) before asking a question.
        You can select sources individually to scope the conversation — especially useful
        when organizing different versions of a document, or comparing two sources side by side.
      </p>

      <figure class="figure">
        <img src={`${figBase}/選擇來源.png`} alt="Left-side source panel, where you can check specific sources to scope the conversation" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>Figure 3. Selecting sources (the chat only answers from the checked ones)</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <!-- Section 4: Chat and citations -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Chat Q&amp;A and citations</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Once the sources are in place, the useful part begins. NotebookLM lets you ask
        questions in chat form, and its answers are grounded in the material inside your
        notebook — <strong>not the kind of answer that goes on at length with no clear origin</strong>.
        Answers come with clear inline citations, so you can check whether the content is reliable.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Viewing a citation is straightforward. When a citation marker appears in the answer,
        hover over it to preview the full cited text; click it directly, and NotebookLM jumps
        to the corresponding place in the original source, letting you check the surrounding
        context. This is part of why NotebookLM suits key-point roundups, source comparison,
        and teaching-material preparation — you not only get an answer, you can verify it
        on the spot.
      </p>

      <section class="concept-card">
        <p class="concept-card__label">The more specific your question, the better the answer</p>
        <p class="concept-card__body">
          When a notebook holds many sources, the clearer the question, the more likely
          NotebookLM is to pick up the passages that actually matter.
        </p>
        <ul class="concept-card__list">
          <li>
            <span class="prompt-bad">"Summarize this"</span>
            → try
            <span class="prompt-good">"Pull out three key points from Chapter 2 related to user behavior"</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="prompt-bad">"What's the difference?"</span>
            → try
            <span class="prompt-good">"Compare how Interview A and Interview B discuss the same issue"</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        NotebookLM is a good fit for "organizing from sources," but only if the sources
        themselves are clear and clean. It is not a magic tool —
        <strong>messy sources usually lead to messy answers</strong>.
      </p>

      <!-- Section 5: Notes -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Saving notes</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        First-time users often treat the chat window as a one-off Q&amp;A area, but the
        <strong>Notes feature is well worth using</strong>. There are two basic ways to do it:
      </p>

      <ol class="start-steps">
        <li class="start-step">
          <span class="start-step__num">A</span>
          <div class="start-step__body">
            <h4 class="start-step__title">Add a note yourself</h4>
            <p class="start-step__desc">
              Type your thoughts or organized notes directly into a new note — good for
              personal takeaways, to-dos, observations, or memos.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="start-step">
          <span class="start-step__num">B</span>
          <div class="start-step__body">
            <h4 class="start-step__title">Save a chat response</h4>
            <p class="start-step__desc">
              When you get a particularly useful answer, press <strong>"Save to notes"</strong>
              at the bottom-left of the response, and it lands in the notes panel on the right.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The value of this feature is that you don't have to scroll back through the chat
        history each time. Important passages, finalized outlines, and phrasing you've already
        verified can all be saved as notes, then refined at your own pace. Each notebook can
        hold up to <strong>1,000 notes</strong>, which is enough room for long-running
        organization.
      </p>

      <section class="caution-card">
        <p class="caution-card__label">⚠️ A quick note</p>
        <p class="caution-card__body">
          Notes <strong>saved from chat responses cannot be edited once created</strong>.
          If you'd rather keep an editable version, it's better to use "Add a note yourself"
          and write it in manually.
        </p>
      </section>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Beyond memos, NotebookLM's notes can go further. You can
        <strong>turn a single note into a source</strong>, or
        <strong>convert all notes into sources at once</strong>.
        This means you can first use chat to draft a set of key points, then feed them back
        in as new sources — grounding later questions on a more condensed, more focused base.
        This works well for teaching outlines, project organization, reading notes, and
        personal knowledge bases.
      </p>

      <blockquote class="pullquote pullquote--primary">
        When you see something good, don't just read it and move on — save it as a note.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Chat history keeps scrolling, but a saved note stays in the notebook.
        You can refine it, reorganize it, or later turn it into a new source.
        That is how NotebookLM shifts from being a Q&amp;A tool into
        <strong>a working surface where content actually accumulates</strong>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .nb-basics {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Header */
  .detail-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-title {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .detail-subtitle {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .platform-note {
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: 0 var(--border-radius) var(--border-radius) 0;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .platform-note__label {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-right: var(--space-2);
    padding: 0 var(--space-2);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  .platform-note strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Section headings */
  .detail-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-paragraph {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .detail-paragraph strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .plan-note {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
  }

  /* Plan comparison table */
  .plan-table-wrapper {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-4);
    overflow-x: auto;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .plan-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    min-width: 36rem;
  }

  .plan-table thead th {
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-4);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 700;
    text-align: left;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .plan-table thead th:first-child {
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  }

  .plan-table__sub {
    display: block;
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-top: 2px;
  }

  .plan-table tbody tr:not(:last-child) {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .plan-table tbody th {
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4);
    text-align: left;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-text);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  .plan-table tbody td {
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4);
    color: var(--color-text);
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  /* Concept card */
  .concept-card {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-4);
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .concept-card__label {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .concept-card__body {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  .concept-card__body strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .concept-card__list {
    margin: var(--space-3) 0 0;
    padding-left: var(--space-5);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  .concept-card__list li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .prompt-bad,
  .prompt-good {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 2px var(--space-2);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
  }

  .prompt-bad {
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    text-decoration: line-through;
  }

  .prompt-good {
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
    color: var(--color-heading);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  /* Caution card */
  .caution-card {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-4);
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--color-text-secondary);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border-radius: 0 var(--border-radius) var(--border-radius) 0;
  }

  .caution-card__label {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .caution-card__body {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  .caution-card__body strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .caution-card__numbered {
    margin: 0;
    padding-left: var(--space-5);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    counter-reset: caution;
    list-style: none;
  }

  .caution-card__numbered li {
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    padding-left: var(--space-3);
    counter-increment: caution;
  }

  .caution-card__numbered li::before {
    content: counter(caution);
    position: absolute;
    left: -1.25rem;
    top: 0;
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 1.25rem;
    height: 1.25rem;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background-color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    color: var(--color-bg);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .caution-card__numbered strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Source chips */
  .source-grid {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: var(--space-2);
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .source-chip {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    color: var(--color-text);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 9999px;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  /* Figure with screenshot */
  .figure {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0;
    padding: var(--space-3);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .figure img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    border-radius: calc(var(--border-radius) - 2px);
  }

  .figure figcaption {
    margin-top: var(--space-3);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-1);
    text-align: center;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  /* Pullquote */
  .pullquote {
    margin: var(--space-8) 0;
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    border-radius: 0 var(--border-radius) var(--border-radius) 0;
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .pullquote--primary {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    border-left-width: 4px;
  }

  /* Start steps */
  .start-steps {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-4) 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
  }

  .start-step {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: var(--space-8);
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
  }

  .start-step__num {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 2rem;
    height: 2rem;
    border-radius: 50%;
    border: 1.5px solid var(--color-accent);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .start-step__body {
    flex: 1;
    padding-top: var(--space-1);
  }

  .start-step__title {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .start-step__desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  /* Mobile */
  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .plan-table thead th,
    .plan-table tbody th,
    .plan-table tbody td {
      padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-3);
    }

    .concept-card,
    .caution-card {
      padding: var(--space-5) var(--space-6);
    }

    .pullquote {
      padding: var(--space-5) var(--space-6);
      font-size: var(--text-base);
    }

    .pullquote--primary {
      font-size: var(--text-lg);
    }

    .start-step {
      gap: var(--space-5);
